<figureCitation box="[1248,1327,365,388]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–41. 39–40" captionStartId="44.[151,269,1645,1669]" captionTargetBox="[274,1314,462,1635]" captionTargetId="figure-290@44.[210,1377,456,1639]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURES 39–41. 39–40. Ventral surface of pronotum. 39. Phloeodes diabolicus; 40. P. plicatus. 41. Lateral view of P. diabolicus hypomeron." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5230765" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5230765/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
), or broad shallow depression (
<figureCitation box="[416,495,400,423]" captionStart="FIGURES 42–46. 42" captionStartId="46.[151,269,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[419,1208,199,1583]" captionTargetId="figure-177@46.[267,1319,150,1624]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURES 42–46. 42. Lateral view of P. venustus hypomeron. 43. Ventral view of tarsus of P. venustus. 44–46. Male genitalia. 44. P. diabolicus; 45. P. plicatus; 46. P. venustus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5230767" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5230767/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
); elytral vestiture variable; elytra with three distinct nodules at start of declivity, two offset medially, and one laterally....................................................................................................................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
